{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596952"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:19:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:19:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15422"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15422"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.03,0.06,0.87,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67323"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8113"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52775"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1704"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7662"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19677"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22543"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67323"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man with chronic hepatitis C infection undergoes a liver biopsy. Microscopic examination reveals hepatocytes arranged in thick trabecular cords (\u0026gt;3 cells thick), with increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio, nuclear pleomorphism, and loss of normal portal architecture (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholangiocarcinoma","Focal nodular hyperplasia","Hepatic adenoma","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Metastatic colorectal carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes classic histological features of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, which commonly develops in the setting of chronic viral hepatitis. The key histological features include trabecular growth pattern, increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio, and loss of normal architecture.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows well-differentiated hepatocytes without nuclear atypia or architectural distortion. \u003Cstrong\u003EFocal nodular hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates a central stellate scar with radiating fibrous septa. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholangiocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows glandular/tubular structures lined by columnar epithelium. \u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic colorectal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically shows well-formed glands with dirty necrosis and does not demonstrate hepatocellular differentiation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hepatocellular carcinoma commonly develops in patients with chronic hepatitis C infection","Key histological features of hepatocellular carcinoma include trabecular pattern, increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio, and loss of normal architecture"],"references":["\u0022Hepatocellular carcinoma histopathology (2) at higher magnification\u0022 by KGH is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Histopathology_of_hepatocellular_carcinoma#/media/File:Hepatocellular_carcinoma_histopathology_(2)_at_higher_magnification.jpg","Janevska D, Chaloska-Ivanova V, Janevski V. Hepatocellular Carcinoma: Risk Factors, Diagnosis and Treatment. Open Access Maced J Med Sci. 2015 Dec 15;3(4):732-6. doi: 10.3889/oamjms.2015.111. Epub 2015 Oct 29. PMID: 27275318; PMCID: PMC4877918.","Asafo-Agyei KO, Samant H. Hepatocellular Carcinoma. [Updated 2023 Jun 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559177/","Balogh J, Victor D 3rd, Asham EH, Burroughs SG, Boktour M, Saharia A, Li X, Ghobrial RM, Monsour HP Jr. Hepatocellular carcinoma: a review. J Hepatocell Carcinoma. 2016 Oct 5;3:41-53. doi: 10.2147/JHC.S61146. PMID: 27785449; PMCID: PMC5063561.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52775"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15422"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21160"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21160"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5teBmTonzVgZULY8CaaYS9NqHmypFI.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5teBmTonzVgZULY8CaaYS9NqHmypFI.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":452}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52775"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T21:02:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T21:02:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8113"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67323"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.